        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use band 7 because (1) the flux (0.5 - 0.9 Jy in 850um band) will be 
the highest and (2) the spatial resolution will be the highest among 
the available bands for polarization observation in Cycle 2. To resolve 
the features shown in Figure 1 in Scientific Justification and to detect 
weak extended emission coming from circumstellar medium, we request 0.12" 
angular resolution with a desired sensitivity per pointing at 0.03 mJy.

Line contamination in the continuum (Band 7):

Kaminski et al. (2013) made line survey observations of this target using 
the SMA. There are relatively strong lines such as SiS, SO2 and 
SiO lines in the base bands. We can reconstruct the continuum from the 
line-free channels on the coarse frequency resolution spectrum in TDM mode.
We expect some of the lines that Kaminski et al (2013) reported may not 
become problem for this project because some of the line emissions may be 
very much extended and we are not going to detect those extended emission 
in this observing setting.  
Even with the restricted band available to regenerate continuum emission, 
there will be no problem as the star is very bright at the band. 
From the measurement by the SMA (Kaminski et al. 2013), 
we might have roughly 4.9 GHz line free channels out of ~ 8GHz total band width 
if all of these emission lines come from compact region for the worst case.  
If we use only these line free channels, 
it will result in about 1.26 times worse sensitivity comparing with 
the sensitivity estimated using the sensitivity calcurator.  


The continuum emission must come much more compact region comparing with the 
area inside the lowest contour of the 
SiO map (roughly corresponds to 300 synthesized beams of area) shown in Figure 1.   
When the expected flux of 0.5 Jy (for the minimum case) is distributed in 
roughly 50 synthesized beams, one beam receives 10 mJy. 

ALMA is the only instrument that allows us to image both compact (coming from 
the photosphere) and extended (inner circumstellar dust) components of  
polarization of the emission in very high signal-to-noise ratio.
We expect to detect _at least_ 3 percent of linear polarization degree based 
on the polarized SiO emission shown in Figure 1 and 2. 
3 % of 10 mJy that one synthesized beam receives corresponds to 0.3 mJy. 
When we consider the factor of line free channel (1.26 as explained above), 
the desired sensitivity wil become 0.038 mJy. 
This is roughly 7.9 times higher than the desired sensitivity per pointing 
estimated by the sensitivity calcurator.  

This observation is to be completed within 3 hours, which is the minimum 
required observing time for any polarization observations including 
calibration observations.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
